# Design tokens (`tokens.json`)

**Source of truth:** `design-system/tokens.json` (Figma export: primitives by breakpoint, semantic by Light/Dark). **Do not** hand-edit `app/design-tokens.css` or `app/ds-tailwind-theme.css` — they are generated. After changing tokens, run `npm run build:tokens`.

**Structure:** See `design-system/design-tokens-structure.md`. Prefer **semantic** tokens for UI meaning (backgrounds, text, borders, states) when a matching token exists; use **primitives** when there is no semantic equivalent.

## In components and CSS

- **Tailwind:** Use theme colors that map to tokens, e.g. `bg-ds-bg-primary`, `text-ds-text-primary`, `border-ds-border-secondary` (pattern: `*-ds-*` from `@theme` in `ds-tailwind-theme.css`).
- **Raw CSS:** Use `var(--ds-…)` variables from the generated palette (same names as in `design-tokens.css`).
- **Consistency:** Reuse the same token for the same role across components (one primary surface color, one default text color, etc.). Avoid parallel “almost the same” hex values.

## Avoid

```tsx
// ❌ Arbitrary values that bypass tokens
className="bg-[#6366F1] text-[#111827]"
```

```tsx
// ✅ Token-backed utilities
className="bg-ds-bg-brand-primary text-ds-text-primary"
```

If the design needs a value that is **not** in `tokens.json`, add or extend the token in `design-system/tokens.json`, run `npm run build:tokens`, then use the new `--ds-*` / `*-ds-*` mapping — do not leave one-off literals in JSX or CSS.
